name: N-hexyl formate
Reason: The compound N-hexyl formate has a formate ester functional group and a hexyl chain. The reference compound for comparison is methanol, which has a melting point of -98 °C. The formate ester generally raises the melting point due to its ability to engage in dipole-dipole interactions, compared to an alcohol which only has hydrogen bonding. However, the long hydrocarbon tail (hexyl group) has a tendency to lower melting points compared to shorter chains due to increased entropy and a more dispersed charge distribution, thus weakening intermolecular interactions. The formate ester functional group could increase the melting point by approximately +20 °C relative to methanol because of increased molecular weight and dipole interactions. The hexyl chain, being 5 carbon units longer than the methyl group in methanol, could decrease the melting point by approximately -5 °C per additional carbon beyond the first one, cumulatively giving -25 °C. Together, the adjustments would be +20 °C for formate ester and -25 °C for the hexyl chain.
